        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Spectral setup: For the five primary targets, we have precise redshifts from muliple optical lines. CO3-2 is centered on those redshifts in band-3. The spectral bandwidth and resolution is picked such that we cover a range of ~2000 km/sec with 12 km/sec spectral resolution. The wide bandwidth we are able to explore the full line of sight depth of the halo in the velocity space. 

Spatial resolution: Naturally we degrade resolution to cover max spatial scales without an extra penalty on the total time request. We found this to be around 2 arcseconds, while still probing 25 arcseconds. This 2 arcsecond spatial resolution is assumed in the mock simulations (Fig. 2).

Largest angular scale: 25 arcseconds. We do not want this reduced. This is driven by the need to capture more of the distant satellites in the angular projection with just one pointing. Note that at the maximum mass scale of interest the halo has a full extent of 220 kpc, but mock simulations in Fig. 2 show probing an extent of roughly 100 kpc, corresponding to 25 arcsec, is adquate.
At the smaller mass scale of interest, 1e12 solar masses, this resolution is adequate to probe 75% of the halo spatial extent.
We emphasize that the measurement is not limited by the spatial resolution and spatial extent as long as we stay around 100 kpc as we have significant spectral resolution to probe the full depth in the velocity space.

Sensitivity: This is determined not by the CO luminosity of the primary targets, which will be bright in CO and detected at very high signal-to-noise ratio, but by the depth of luminosity we would like to reach for the satellites. To begin we assume a goal for the depth in the total IR luminosity to be roughly 1e11 solar luminosities, but adjust given sensitivity to 2e11 solar luminosities in practice later. 

We first convert L-IR to L-prime CO1-0 luminosity using the observed power-law scaling relation of IR lum to CO1-0 L' lum in Bothwell et al. (also Daddi et al). There is a large scatter so we take the bottom end of the scatter of L-prime CO1-0 values at the fixed L-FIR (at L-IR=1e11, L-prime 1-0 is 5e8 K km/s pc2. We then convert L-prime CO1-0 to a CO3-2 assuming a SLED like Milky-Way for the satellites. We convert to S_nu delta nu in Jy km/s. We then get a S_nu assuming a 250 km/sec dispersion for each satellite. 

The typical CO3-2 line flux density is at the level of 0.15 mJy in a 100 MHz bandwidth (=250 km/sec) when L-IR is 1e11 solar luminosities. 

At the end of the day we need a sensitivity of at least 0.15 mJy in 100 MHz spectral resolution can detect L-IR&gt;5e11 solar lum galaxies better than 3 sigma (as primaries have L&gt;5e12, we detect satellites down to 10th of lum). We only need the line peak to get relative velocity for the dynamical halo mass measurement and do not need to spectrally or spatially resolve CO emission from each satellite galaxy. We also do not need the precise CO line flux or luminosity for the primary science, but ancillary science goals do. For those we will make use of parallel continuum observations to accurately calibrate the line intensity from the continuum. The depth, spectral resolution, and largest extent probed are used in Fig. 2 mock simulations.

Each integration is slightly less than 40 minutes as we need to reach sufficient depth for a minimum (=10) number of satellites for the dynamical halo mass measurement with 5 primary targets. The mininum requirement is based on simulations for a 6 sigma identification of 1e12 vs 1e13 halo mass scales.

We do not think it is necessary to explain the data analysis process. We will make maximum use of the US ALMA Science Center resources. Furthermore Co-Is have significant experiences with CO spectral line/cube data. The modeling for the halo mass measurement will follow well-established techniques with developments as needed for ALMA data, if any. The technique and new developments will be presented when publishing our results.



</prj:justificationText>
