    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The successful models of galaxy formation and evolution fail to explain how and why FIR/sub-mm bright dusty starburst galaxies formed in the universe. A conflicting issue is that the halo mass scale for efficient star-formation is at 1e12 solar masses, an order of magnitude below the suggested mass scale for dusty starbursts from clustering studies of 1e13 solar masses. The clustering halo mass scale could be an overestimate if the so-called merger bias, a somewhat controversial issue, is at play for on-going compact mergers, such as dusty starbursts. We propose satellite dynamics as a direct measure of the halo mass scale, focussing on a sample of five Herschel-selected luminous galaxies (L &gt; 5e12 solar luminosities) at z of 2.5 in ALMA band-3 with the CO3-2 line. Satellites of those luminous starbursts will be detected down to a IR luminosity depth of 1e11 solar luminosities. By stacking the sample of five targets in projected velocity-position space we can distinguish between the two scenarios of 1e12 and 1e13 solar masses at more than six sigma, even after accounting for dominant systematics such as high-z faint interlopers.</prp:abstract>
